

Robert White (May 28, 1876 &lt;U+2013&gt; August 15, 1935) was an American lawyer and politician in the U.S. state of West Virginia. White served four consecutive terms as the Prosecuting Attorney for Hampshire County (1912&lt;U+2013&gt;1928) and served one term in the West Virginia Senate (1930&lt;U+2013&gt;1934) representing the state's Fifteenth Senatorial District in the 40th and 41st Sessions of the West Virginia Legislature. During the 1933 legislative year, White served as the floor leader for the Democratic Party members of the West Virginia Senate.
White was a member of the White political family of Virginia and West Virginia and was the son of Hampshire County Clerk of Court and West Virginia Fish Commission President Christian Streit White (1839&lt;U+2013&gt;1917) and the grandson of Hampshire County Clerk of Court John Baker White (1794&lt;U+2013&gt;1862). White was a nephew of West Virginia Attorney General Robert White (1833&lt;U+2013&gt;1915).
Early life and education
Robert White was born on May 28, 1876 in Romney, West Virginia.123 He was the second child of Hampshire County Clerk of Court Christian Streit White (1839&lt;U+2013&gt;1917) with his second wife Catharine Steele White (1837&lt;U+2013&gt;1869)45 and the third eldest of his father's five children.6 White was a grandson of Hampshire County Clerk of Court John Baker White (1794&lt;U+2013&gt;1862)7 and a great-grandson of the prominent Virginia judge Robert White (1759&lt;U+2013&gt;1831).8 His uncle Robert White (1833-1915) served as Attorney General of West Virginia and his brother John Baker White (1868&lt;U+2013&gt;1944) was a military officer and later served as a Charleston city councilman and president of the West Virginia Board of Control.
White received his early education in the public schools of Romney, and attended Romney's Potomac Academy.9 He commenced his career in public service at the age of 1610 when he began serving as the Deputy Clerk of Court in the office of his father, Christian Streit White, who was then serving as Clerk of Court for Hampshire County.11 In 1894, White graduated from Potomac Academy at the age of 18.1213 Two years later, he began his studying jurisprudence in the West Virginia University College of Law in Morgantown.1415 He graduated from the West Virginia University College of Law in 1899,161718 earning a Bachelor of Laws degree.19 White cast his first vote for Democratic Party presidential nominee William Jennings Bryan in the United States presidential election of 1900.20
Law career
Following his graduation in 1899 from West Virginia University,21 White returned to Romney and established a law practice.2223 In 1903, he became associated with his father Christian Streit White in a law practice, following the conclusion of his father's term as Hampshire County Clerk of Court.24 White continued to practice law with his father until 1912, when he was elected to his first term as Prosecuting Attorney for Hampshire County.2526
Political career
Before the age of 21, White represented Hampshire County as a delegate to a West Virginia Democratic Party state convention.27
In 1912, won election to serve as the Prosecuting Attorney for Hampshire County.2829 He was elected to the position four times, and served four four-year terms from 1912 to 1928.303132 While serving as the county's prosecuting attorney, White was a strong proponent of the Good Roads Movement33 and under his leadership, the first concrete bridge was constructed in Hampshire County by the County Court.34
Between 1917 and 1921,353637 in addition to serving as the county's prosecuting attorney, White served as the Commissioner of School Lands383940 and as one of the Chancery Commissioners for Hampshire County, along with Joshua Soule Zimmerman and James Sloan Kuykendall.414243
In 1930, White was elected to serve in the West Virginia Senate representing the state's Fifteenth Senatorial District.444546 He served in the 40th and 41st Sessions of the West Virginia Legislature and completed his term in 1934.474849 White served as the floor leader for the West Virginia Senate's Democratic Party members during the 1933 legislative year.50
Affiliations
White served as a master of the Masonic Lodge,51 and was affiliated with the Odd Fellows.52
Personal life

Marriage and issue
White married on January 7, 1903 in Washington, D.C.5354 to Mabel Glasscock Fitch,555657 the only child and daughter of E. H. Fitch and his wife Laura Glasscock Fitch.58 Fitch was a native of Vanceburg, Kentucky59 and she attended Marshall College while her family resided in Huntington.60 Fitch completed her education in Washington, D.C.61 White and his wife Mabel had five children:62

John Baker White6364 (born February 11, 1904)65
Mabel Glasgow White Cornwell6667 (born February 18, 1906),68 married James Leighton Cornwell on August 25 1926 in Hampshire County69
Elizabeth Steele White7071 (born April 23, 1908)72
Roberta Huston White McFarland737475 (born June 18, 1912),76 married William Frank McFarland on June 13, 1936 in New Cumberland77
Robert White, Jr.78

White's wife Mabel was an active member of the Presbyterian church79 and died on July 5, 191580 and was interred at Indian Mound Cemetery in Romney.81
Later life and death
White never remarried following his wife's death in 1915.82 After several months of illness,83 White died at his residence in Romney on August 15, 1935 at the age of 59848586 due to arteriosclerosis and myocarditis.8788 White was interred with Masonic rites on Saturday afternoon, August 17, 1935899091 at Indian Mound Cemetery in Romney.929394
